\section{Regex}

\begin{note}
Regular expressions (regex) closely related to the glob:
\begin{enumerate}
\item
The glob is generally used for finding files based on their \emph{name},
and regex is used for finding files based on their \emph{contents}.
\item
Regex has a syntax similar to he glob,
but the semantics is slightly different.
It is easy to get them confused, so pay attention!
\end{enumerate}
You are responsible for the following regex syntax:

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{ll}
\toprule
Pattern & Matches \\
\midrule
\texttt{.} & exactly one character \\
\texttt{*} & zero or more of preceding element \\
\texttt{+} & one or more of preceding element \\
\texttt{?} & zero or one of preceding element \\
\texttt{[abc]} & one character in the set \\
\texttt{[\textasciicircum abc]} & one character not in the set \\
\texttt{\textasciicircum} & start of string \\
\texttt{\$} & end of string \\
\texttt{(a|b)} & alternation (a or b) \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}
\end{note}

\begin{note}
For space reasons, I am giving you a very limited set of regex/glob patterns below.
You should try creating your own problems with your own regex/glob patterns to check your understanding.
This is another example of me trying to get you to learn-how-to-learn.
\end{note}

\subsection{In the shell}

\begin{note}
The shell program for using regex is called \texttt{grep}.
It is so commonly used that programmers often say we are ``grepping'' for something whenever we are ``searching'' for something
(similar to how muggles will often say they are ``googling'' something even if they are using another search engine like bing, baidu, or yandex.
\end{note}
